Another note on wyverns.  I've been relevelling my wizard, and they're much easier at lower level than they used to be back in the day.  I attribute this to KEI and the resist changes.  I was single-kiting them at 39 with our 39 magic nuke and BoF.  I started reliably quadding them with CoF at about 43-44.  Takes a BoF refresh about 3/5th of the way through the kite because CoF takes a long time, but it's killer xp at those levels and well worth it.<br>
<br>
Of course pre-luclin wyverns and raptors were some of the few easy xp quads, so I did them when they were greening out just because there wasn't much else for selection.  These days I wouldn't touch either once they start significantly light blueing on you - Luclin offers plenty of blue alternatives.  I saw my first (about 20% or so??) Lt Blue wyverns at 52, so 52 was my last level there this time around - whereas back in the day I stayed there until around 54-55-ish.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ministatius>Ministatius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/24/02 2:30 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> well done</span><hr size=1> Fantastic post, very comprehensive, thasnk for taking the time to write it out.... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=teamnoir>teamnoir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/30/02 7:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Quad Kiting Locations Guide - Rough Draft</span><hr size=1> Some additions.  I assume kei at all times, so some of my levels are a little lower than some.<br>
<br>
Wyverns begin to cyan out at 52 and the exp plummets.  They are quite doable when EW begins to green out.  Wyverns are not casters.  Drakes are.  Drakes also dispell.  You can take them by singling, rooting, and nuking from max range.  Also beware Yvolcarn.  He looks like a wyvern, spawns like a wyvern, but is immune to run speed changes like root/shackle.  Know where he is before you pull.<br>
<br>
Also, you can pull from the tower if you either run up it, or target through the window and sotf while near.  Be careful of the bulgar (or whatever they are called, leader is immune to run speed changes and will aggro nearest.)<br>
<br>
With kei, I could hold large raptor island without trouble at 52.  I did 3aa, then 53 there.  I'm killing them as fast as they spawn and maintaining mana.  At 52, manaskin helped.  At 53, with regen3, I think it's cheaper to take a few hits and I'm not having any trouble with mana.<br>
<br>
EW was good as early as 34 on walrus up to 44 or so.  Rhinos run exactly as fast as ulthorks and you can mix the quads.  They aren't social in the same way, so you'll need to finish them a little differently.  For walrus, there's another/better location south of kael entrance.  Many walrus, plenty of space.  Avoid man-o-war.  Less space than north shore, but less competition and all walrus.  No waiting for spawns.<br>
<br>
Iceclad, panthers.  I taught myself to kite on these guys in the low 30's before moving on to dervishes.  Camp site is the pirate island.  Low loot, low-medium difficulty.  Pull them to the island's edge and kite along it to avoid wanderers.  You can quad them at 34, or dervishes, but you get better loot &amp; exp from EW walrus at that level.<br>
<br>
Great Divide, wolves around the luclin spires are very doable.  Avoid giants.  I was doing this in the mid and upper 40's before I learned about spirocs.  Low loot, medium difficulty.  Exp isn't great, but includes useful faction.<br>
<br>
I just tried Tro Jeg.  At 53, all blue and I can do them.  They take me about 3m to nail a quad.  Still haven't figured out how to pull them gracefully, though.<br>
<br>
Awlin <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=teamnoir>teamnoir</A> at: 12/30/02 10:27:18 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lanoril>Lanoril</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/1/03 7:58 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Quad Kiting Locations Guide - Rough Draft</span><hr size=1> Minimum Level: 29<br>
Maximum Level: 34<br>
Zone Name: Marus Seru<br>
Camp Area/LOC: The plains just outside the Sanctus Seru zone entrance<br>
Mob List(HP) : Greyhoppers; Zelniaks; Lightcrawlers*<br>
Availability (1-&gt;10): 10 There are so many mobs and so few people here (on my server, at least) that availability has never been an issue for me.<br>
Loot Ranking (1-&gt;10): 1 No coin or &quot;interesting&quot; items in my experience.  Various caster research items (runes, pages, and such), pelts, and hides.<br>
Diff.Ranking (1-&gt;10): 4 For newbie quadkiters the long agro range of zelniaks can be difficult to get used to.  (EDIT: a &quot;gigantic lightcrawler&quot; that cannot be rooted and runs faster than blood of the wolf SoW occasionally spawns here, too.)  For people like me, returned from a long break and starting over, it shouldn't be too difficult.<br>
Faction Affected:  None<br>
<br>
*Stonegrabbers also, if you feel especially brave, but there are a LOT of stonegrabbers and they are very social.  I haven't tried because it doesn't seem worth the effort with so many other easier things to pick on.  But the looting would be better--they drop gold earrings occasionally. (EDIT: I just tried these and if you are careful you can avoid all the extras that would agro.  They also drop armour dying materials.  FURTHER EDIT: The stonegrabbers are still dark blue with the occasional light blue at level 34, so I imagine the area is viable through 35, but probably not worth it with OT and other areas listed that are, imho, better.)<br>
<br>
My main interest in quadkiting here is because I was a master tailor before I took my long break, and wanted an easy place to collect pelts to take me to a moderate level again without spending too much plat.  The greyhoppers drop LQ hides frequently and regular hides almost as frequently.  My tailor skill went from about 20 to 88ish here over the course my XP'ing.<br>
<br>
These critters start to turn light blue at 30 (but I'm currently 31 and have not yet found a green hopper or lightcrawler; some green zelniaks), so XP wise it may not be terribly worth it to you.<br>
<br>
The camp area is very wide open though, with hills around the edges (that you should avoid because of the usual pathing and line-of-sight  issues).  Very minimal danger of adds if you pay attention and rarely will you have people complaining about you.<br>
<br>
PS: I tried north of the Neth Lair entrance a lot, but there is too much hilly terrain and too many chances for adds there for my taste. <p><HR>
<b>Lanoril "Uber Lef" Malumaureus</b><BR>
Motto: <i>The fires are burning down</i>

